b'The beginning of football season is always met with cheers. But for the @cbfapr , a youth team of 13 to 15 year olds that is coached by volunteers, the celebration was short-lived: someone had stolen the team\xe2\x80\x99s tractor that was essential for using the mobile lighting system. Those who live in Calgary and in the north know that the daylight hours drop off sharply at the end of the summer, and field lights are necessary for teams to practice and play outdoors. 

The Bantam Stampeders did everything they could - they successfully raised $7,000 to replace the equipment; a major feat given the hardships faced during the pandemic. And while that amount is impressive, it was $3,000 short of the goal. 

When we heard of this shortfall, we found a way to fill the gap and arranged to cover the difference and bring lights to the field. 

A Bantam Stampeder parent, Ali Zeeshan, said, \xe2\x80\x9cThey say that small things can make a big difference, well, Canadian Tire has made it here\xe2\x80\x9d.'

b'We can all agree that 2020 has been a year of change. One thing that has remained constant is the generosity and community spirit of our Associate Dealers in Quebec. As a show of solidarity with folks across the province, Associate Dealers from the 100 Canadian Tire stores across Quebec joined forces to establish the \xe2\x80\x9c100 stores, 100 more than 150 donations\xe2\x80\x9d initiative, as a way of supporting charities and causes that help improve the quality of life of children and families within their community. So far, more than $310,000 has been donated, giving kids and their families a greater chance at a safer year.'

b'They say it takes a village to raise a child - and if there was ever a time for a village to step up, this is it. At least that\xe2\x80\x99s what Ranjit Soman, Associate Dealer of Flin Flon\xe2\x80\x99s Canadian Tire, believes. \n\nOne way this small but mighty store felt it could help was to make sure free sanitizer was in healthy supply at every school in the area, including those in First Nations communities and in remote locations of Manitoba and Saskatchewan. A total of 440 litres of sanitizer has been distributed among eleven schools. Ranjit hopes this donation can support teachers, janitorial staff, and give parents peace of mind as kids attend class this year.'

b'At Canadian Tire, we do our best to be there for our neighbours, and in this case, that includes lending a hand to a young Ontario farmer who hit hard times. 

Three years ago, Tom Taylor followed his heart\xe2\x80\x99s dream: he left the big city to start Madawaska Maple, a maple syrup farm in the Algonquin Highlands. COVID-19 has sharply decreased tourists to his sugar shack and there have been fewer sales of Madawaska Maple products as a result - but Tom carried on bravely. That is until a fire recently ravaged his property, destroying the trailer he was living in along with much of his tools and equipment. 
When Tom\xe2\x80\x99s family reached out to the community to see if anybody could help, Marilyn Rubin, Associate Dealer of the Canadian Tire in Bancroft ON, answered the call. Marilyn arranged for Madawaska Maple to receive a free Mastercraft compressor and a Skilsaw chop saw. Our corporate office also provided a gift card for Tom to use as he sees fits. 

It\xe2\x80\x99s our hope that Tom can continue to do what he does best - making that sweet maple syrup!'

b'After hearing a group of Dealers received a surplus of hand sanitizer, we immediately knew we had to find a way to repurpose this inventory to help those in need. We purchased this inventory back & donated all proceeds to local United Way chapters. In total there were 2,232 pails which benefited 26 organizations across the country including @foodbankbarrie . \nMore than ever, we\xe2\x80\x99re ready to help Canadians where ever possible through these difficult times. Visit our COVID Relief Fund webpage for more on what we\xe2\x80\x99re doing to help during this pandemic.'

b'Canadian Tire Dealers Glenn Butt & Paul Brennan wanted to help their community & local small businesses when the City of Burlington mandated masks due to the evolving stages of the pandemic. Glenn reached out to the Mayor\xe2\x80\x99s office & the Fairview shopping mall to help coordinate the distribution of 20,000 ASTM masks & pails of sanitizer. These were donated directly from the Canadian Tire COVID Response Fund so the pressure to supply these to customers was lifted for many small business owners. We can\xe2\x80\x99t thank our Dealers enough for the continued generosity & support they are showing in their local communities :folded_hands:'

b'Some people are big thinkers. Others have huge hearts. We believe Jason & Karen Butorac easily reside in both camps.\nThese Canadian Tire store Dealers in Yellowknife, NWT seem to have covered all the bases of who in their community could use help most during this pandemic. Jason & Karen donated over $8,000 to Healthcare workers, the elderly, women & children in crisis, & those who have lost their jobs. Their donation also included 2,700 masks. The admiration & gratitude directed to you from your community in Yellowknife is echoed by everyone in the Canadian Tire family. Thank you for your generosity & compassion during this pandemic :folded_hands:'

b'As businesses across the country remain closed in an effort to slow the spread of COVID-19, hundreds of thousands of Canadians find themselves with a much smaller income - or worse - without a paycheque at all. Putting food on the table for themselves & their family have become a real concern for many.\nFive compassionate Canadian Tire Dealers in Ontario\xe2\x80\x99s Waterloo Region couldn\xe2\x80\x99t bear the thought of people in their community going hungry, so they stepped up in a massive way: they pooled their resources & wrote a $75,000 cheque to @foodbankwatreg . This generous donation translates to a whopping 225,000 meals for local residents in need. Joe C, Brian D, Chris G, Brandon L, Phil M- you are all heroes & we cannot express how proud we are to have you in the Canadian Tire Family. Thank you for making a real difference :folded_hands:'

b'The celebrations are a little more intimate this year, but the passion is as strong as ever. Wherever you are in this great big land, have a great one, Canada. Plus, in partnership with CBC, we\xe2\x80\x99re giving away an amazing summer prize pack. Send us your best summer snapshot and you could win! Enter now from the link in our bio.'

b'Like so many Canadians, we are incredibly grateful to frontline healthcare workers who have played a pivotal role in saving the lives of those affected by COVID-19. With short supply of PPE products & an environment of uncertainty, healthcare workers continue to accomplish amazing work. To show gratitude & support to these frontline healthcare workers we have donated $500,000 to @the_frontline_fund , a coalition of more than 165 hospital foundations across the country created in response to the global pandemic. \nIn addition to providing PPE & medical supplies like masks, ventilators, & testing equipment to hospitals across Canada, proceeds from @the_frontline_fund will also deliver healthcare workers the personal support they need. This includes meals, access to mental health counselling & hotel rooms for self isolation when not on duty. The funding also supports research such as clinical drug trials & vaccine development.\nFor the latest info on what we\xe2\x80\x99re doing to slow the spread of the virus, please continue to visit our COVID-19 Response page.'

b'@multyhomelp , Canadian Tire store #192 (Leslie St. & Sheppard Ave.) & @paradise_dev came together in an inclusive community event to recognize the amazing work at @northyorkgeneral during the current pandemic & to donate 1,000 #BrighterDaysAhead rainbow doormats to select hospital workers. @multyhomelp staff came up with the brilliant idea to manufacture the doormats reflecting the rainbow symbol of hope & to salute our healthcare heroes that have evolved out of the current pandemic.\nImmediately following the doormat giveaway, Canadian Tire store #192 will be selling #BrighterDaysAhead doormats to the public. All proceeds will be going to @northyorkgeneral Foundation\xe2\x80\x99s COVID-19 Emergency Response Fund, which was established to support the hospital\xe2\x80\x99s ability to address emerging critical needs. #BrighterDaysAhead'

b'Building off our long-standing partnership with @redcrosscanada , we provided $1M to help them reach communities who need it the most during these trying times. Together, we are supporting the health and well-being of Canadians through access to field hospitals, relief supplies, isolation sites, and emergency food delivery programs like in Toronto. In partnership with @cityofto , @redcrosscanada is delivering food boxes and shelf stable food items to individuals who are isolated in their homes and have no options for food delivery. Red Cross personnel deliver up to 250 boxes every single day.\nLink in bio for more info on what we\xe2\x80\x99re doing to help communities during this time.'

b'As hospitals and frontline healthcare workers are continuing to face COVID-19 outbreaks daily, the need for PPE remains high. Husband and wife Associate Dealers Dave and Pam Malcolmson recognized this demand for PPE supply at their local Queensway Carleton Hospital in Ottawa Ontario and sprang into action donating 4,000 ASTM masks to help keep frontline healthcare workers protected.\nWe can\xe2\x80\x99t thank our Dealers enough for the continued generosity and support they are showing in their local communities :folded_hands:\nLink in bio for the latest information on what we\xe2\x80\x99re doing to help slow the spread of COVID-19.'
b'Have a drink in a chair made out of 24,000 bottle caps this long weekend. #MyCANVASStyle'
b'A long weekend means even more time to spend with the family. What have you got planned for your extra day?'

b'As many of you know, this week we are celebrating all the nurses in our lives. Every moment in their day is dedicated to their patients, and so few moments are for themselves.
With cafeterias shut down at Royal Victoria Regional Health Centre, picking up coffee was a challenge for medical staff. Eager to help, Associate Canadian Tire Dealer Paul Pollock supplied every work station at the centre with a Keurig machine, so staff can enjoy coffee time a little more often.
How are you celebrating nurses in your life this week? Tag or DM us your story. We\xe2\x80\x99ll be featuring these on our IG story for the rest of the week.
Thank you #HealthHeroes :red_heart_selector: #NursesWeek'
b'We may be celebrating a little differently this year, but the love remains the same. Wishing every mom out there, a happy Mother\xe2\x80\x99s Day.'

b'For Canadians with loved ones on the frontline, it can be unsettling to think about potential consequences if PPE were not available to them. This is especially true for Thornhill Canadian Tire Associate Dealer, Craig Knapp, whose daughter is a Neonatal ICU nurse at Mount Sinai Hospital in Toronto, Ontario. Inspired by the work and dedication he sees from his daughter, Knapp stepped in to provide some much-needed relief for the hospital by donating 40,000 surgical masks to staff members. Big thanks to Craig for his donation and to all of the frontline healthcare workers for all of your efforts and dedication. :Canada:\nLink in bio for the latest information on what we\xe2\x80\x99re doing to slow the spread of the virus.'

b'Canadian Tire stores in London, Ontario have joined in on the effort to keep frontline workers at their local hospital safe. Stores on Dundas Street, Hyde Park Road, Wellington Road South, and Wonderland Road made a significant combined donation of $30,000 to the @lhsccanada in response to their urgent needs. Hats off to our local London teams for their inspiring effort to keep us all safe. \nFor the latest information on what we\xe2\x80\x99re doing to slow the spread of the virus, please continue to visit out COVID-19 Response Page. Link in bio.'

b"As High River, Alberta was faced with a sudden outbreak of COVID-19, the local Canadian Tire team sprang into action to help create an emergency roadside testing station. Using a refuge tent, a Jumpstart canopy and pails as pylons in addition to donating tables, chairs, hand sanitizer, disinfectant and spray bottles, the team helped frontline workers administer hundreds of tests a day. Our deepest thanks to frontline workers across Canada for your selfless efforts to keep us all safe. Visit the link in bio to learn more about how we're supporting frontline workers and communities through the Canadian Tire COVID-19 Response Fund."

b'As part of the Canadian Tire Corporation COVID-19 Response Fund, Canadian Tire Retail and @markscanada delivered 1,000 masks and 130 scrubs to staff members and volunteers at Markham Ontario\xe2\x80\x99s Participation House. Nice teaming up with you @hchickwick ! Stay tuned for more donation stories from our Canadian Tire COVID-19 Response Fund.'

b'We know how important it is for Canadian communities to have the things they need because we\xe2\x80\x99ve been a part of them for nearly 100 years. To show our support we\xe2\x80\x99re donating $5M to Canada\xe2\x80\x99s Frontline Healthcare and Community Workers, because values matter more now than ever.'

b'From coast to coast we\xe2\x80\x99ve always cared about the well-being of our customers, employees, and communities. To show our support we\xe2\x80\x99re donating $5M to Canada\xe2\x80\x99s frontline healthcare and community workers. As part of the donation, $1M is going to Canadian Red Cross, $1M to United Way Centraide Canada, and $3M in PPE and essential products from across our family of companies. Plus, collectively, our Associate Dealers have donated 160,000 masks, 164,000 pairs of gloves and 20,000 litres of hand sanitizer to hospitals and those in need. We know how important it is for Canadian communities to have the things they need because we\xe2\x80\x99ve been part of them for nearly 100 years. And we want to do everything we can to help, because values matter more now than ever.'
